'''Andhra Pradesh'''&lt;!--Do not add any link to wowtelugu.com or fullastrology.com. See talk page for details.--&gt; ({{indic | lang=te | indic=ఆంధ్ర ప్రదేశ్ |trans=Āndhra Pradēś }}, {{IPA-hns|aːnd̪ʱrə prəd̪eːʃ||Andhra.ogg}},) abbreviated '''A.P.''', is a state situated on the southeastern coast of [[India]]. It is India's [[List of states and territories of India by area|fourth largest state by area]] and [[List of states and union territories of India by population|fifth largest by population]]. Its capital and largest city by population is [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]].  The State has the second-longest coastline of {{convert|972|km|mi|abbr=on}} among all the States in India.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.aponline.gov.in/quick%20links/apfactfile/apfactmain.html |title=Citizen Help |publisher=APOnline |date=1 November 1956|accessdate=3 March 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;  The primary official language of Andhra Pradesh is [[Telugu language|Telugu]] and [[Urdu]] is the secondary official language in some places,&lt;ref name=Index&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.aponline.gov.in/quick%20links/departments/school%20education%20(ssa%20wing)/directorate%20of%20a%20p%20open%20school%20society/introduction/index.html|title=AP Online, Index.html|format=PDF|work=Andhra Pradesh official website|accessdate=16 January 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; while other languages spoken in Andhra Pradesh are [[Hindi]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Kannada]]. 10281 persons declare English as their first language in Andhra Pradesh according to the 2001 census.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.lisindia.net/English/Eng_Demo.html#top&lt;/ref&gt;

Andhra Pradesh lies between 12°41' and 22°N latitude and 77° and 84°40'E longitude, and is bordered by [[Maharashtra]], [[Chhattisgarh]] and [[Odisha]] in the north, the [[Bay of Bengal]] in the East, [[Tamil Nadu]] to the south and [[Karnataka]] to the west.  Andhra Pradesh is historically called the &quot;''Rice Bowl of India''&quot;.  More than 77% of its crop is rice; Andhra Pradesh produced 17,796,000 tonnes of rice in 2006.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title= Rough rice production (000 t) in India, by state, 1961–2006|url= http://www.irri.org/science/ricestat/data/may2008/WRS2008-Table07.pdf |date= May 2008|publisher=International Rice Research Institute |accessdate=25 August 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Two major rivers, the [[Godavari River|Godavari]] and the [[Krishna River|Krishna]], run across the state.  The small enclave ({{convert|30|km2}}) of [[Yanam, India|Yanam]], a district of [[Puducherry]], lies in the Godavari Delta in the northeast of the state.

On 1 November 1956, the [[States Reorganization Act]] formed Andhra Pradesh by merging Telugu-speaking areas of [[Hyderabad State]] and the Telugu-speaking part of the [[Madras Presidency]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Know Hyderabad&quot;&gt;{{cite web |title=Know Hyderabad: History|url=http://hyderabadonline.in/Profile/History/ |publisher=Pan India Network |year=2010 |accessdate=5 October 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==History==
Main : [[History of Andhra Pradesh|History Of Andhra Pradesh]]

An Andhra tribe was mentioned in the [[Sanskrit epics]] such as [[Aitareya Brahmana]] (800 BCE) and [[Mahabharata]] (400 BCE).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.aponline.gov.in/quick%20links/hist-cult/history.html |title=History and Culture-History |publisher=APonline |date=|accessdate=3 March 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Natya Shastra]] written by [[Bharata Muni|Bharatha]] (1st century BCE) also mentions the Andhra people.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://teluguuniversity.ac.in/Language/prachina_telugu_note.html |title=TeluguUniversity.ac.in |publisher=TeluguUniversity.ac.in |date= |accessdate=7 March 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; The roots of the [[Telugu language]] have been seen on inscriptions found near the [[Guntur]] district&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/12/20/stories/200712204820600.htm|title=Andhra Pradesh News : Telugu is 2,400 years old, says ASI |publisher=The Hindu |date=20 December 2007 |accessdate=15 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; and from others dating to the rule of Renati Cholas in the 5th century CE.&lt;ref&gt;Indian Epigraphy, R. Saloman, [[Oxford University Press]], 1998,
ISBN 0-19-509984-2, p. 106&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Megasthenes]], a [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] traveller and geographer who visited the Court of [[Chandragupta Maurya]] (322–297 BCE), mentioned that the region had three fortified towns and an army of 100,000 infantry, 200 cavalry, and 1,000 elephants{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}.[[Buddhist]] books reveal that Andhras established their huts or tents near the [[Godavari River]] at that time.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}

Inscriptional evidence shows that there was an early kingdom in [[coastal Andhra]] (Guntur District) ruled first by Kuberaka and then by his son Varun, with Pratipalapura ([[Bhattiprolu]]) as the capital. Around the same time, Dhanyakatakam/[[Dharanikota]] (present day [[Amaravati, Andhra Pradesh|Amaravati]]) appears to have been an important place, which was visited by [[Gautama Buddha]]. According to the ancient [[Tibetan people|Tibetan]] scholar [[Taranatha]]: &quot;On the full moon of the month [[Chaitra]] in the year following his enlightenment, at the great [[stupa]] of Dhanyakataka, the Buddha emanated the [[mandala]] of 'The Glorious Lunar Mansions' ([[Kalachakra]])&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;Helmutt Hoffmann, &quot;Buddha's Preaching of the Kalachakra [[Tantra]] at the Stupa of Dhanyakataka,&quot; ''German Scholars on India'', Vol. I. PP. 136–140. (Varanasi, 1973)&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.kalacakra.org/history/khistor2.htm |title=Kalacakra.org |publisher=Kalacakra.org |date=8 August 2010 |accessdate=7 March 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Kakateeya Sculpture.jpg|thumb|left|[[Kakatiya dynasty|Kakatiya]] sculpture at [[Warangal]]]]
Literary evidence shows that long before Satavahanas, a legendary king named [[Āndhra Viṣhṇu]] ruled in and around the [[Diviseema]] region of Andhra Pradesh. After his reign, people came to believe that he had an amsa of the divine savior Lord Maha Vishnu himself. Perhaps in his honor, people dedicated a new temple now located at [[Srikakulam Village|Srikākuḷam]], [[Krishna District]]. The lord of the temple is known as Āndhra Viṣhṇu or Srikākuḷāndhra Viṣhṇu.

The [[Maurya Empire|Mauryans]] extended their rule over Andhra in the 4th century BC. With the fall of the Maurya Empire in the 3rd century BC, the [[Satavahana dynasty|Satavahanas]] became independent. After the decline of the Satavahanas in 220 CE, the [[Ikshvaku dynasty]], [[Pallava]]s, [[Ananda Gotrika]]s, [[Rashtrakuta]]s, [[Vishnukundina]]s, [[Eastern Chalukyas]], and [[Chola Dynasty|Cholas]] ruled the land. During this period, Telugu emerged as a popular language, supplanting [[Prakrit]] and [[Sanskrit]].&lt;ref&gt;Epigraphica Indica, 27: 220–228&lt;/ref&gt; Telugu was made the official language by the [[Vishnukundina]] kings (5th and 6th centuries), who ruled from their capital city of [[Vengi]]. Eastern [[Chalukyas]] ruled for a long period after the decline of Vishnukundinas; their capital was also Vengi. As early as the 1st century CE, Chalukyas were mentioned as being vassals and chieftains under the Satavahanas and later under the Ikshvakus. The Chalukya ruler [[Rajaraja Narendra]] ruled [[Rajahmundry]] around 1022 CE.

The battle of [[Palnadu]] (1182) resulted in the weakening of the Eastern Chalukya dynasty and led to the emergence of the [[Kakatiya dynasty]] in the 12th and 13th centuries CE. The Kakatiyas were at first vassals of the Rashtrakutas, and ruled over a small territory near Warangal. Eventually all the Telugu lands were united by the Kakatiyas. In 1323 CE, [[Delhi Sultanate|Delhi Sultan]] [[Ghiyath al-Din Tughluq]] sent a large army under Ulugh Khan to conquer the Telugu country and captured Warangal. King Prataparudra was taken prisoner. [[Musunuri Nayaks]] recaptured Warangal from the Delhi Sultanate in 1326 CE and ruled for fifty years. Inspired by their success, the [[Vijayanagara Empire]], one of the greatest empires in the history of Andhra Pradesh and India, was founded by [[Harihara]] and [[Bukka]], who served as treasury officers of the Kakatiyas of Warangal.&lt;ref&gt;Robert Sewell, ''A Forgotten Empire (Vijayanagar): A contribution to the history of India'', Chapter 2 [http://www.gutenberg.org/dirs/etext02/fevch10.txt Gutenberg.org]&lt;/ref&gt; In 1347 CE, an independent Muslim state, the [[Bahmani Sultanate]], was established in [[south India]] by [[Ala-ud-Din Bahman Shah]] in a revolt against the Delhi Sultanate. The [[Qutb Shahi dynasty]] held sway over the Andhra country for about two hundred years from the early part of the 16th century to the end of the 17th century.{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}
In [[Colonial India]], [[Northern Circars]] became part of the British [[Madras Presidency]]. Eventually this region emerged as the [[Coastal Andhra]] region. Later the [[Nizam]] rulers of Hyderabad ceded five territories to the British which eventually emerged as [[Rayalaseema]] region. The Nizams retained control of the interior provinces as the [[Princely state]] of [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]], acknowledging British rule in return for local autonomy. Meanwhile, the [[French colonial empire|French]] occupied [[Yanam (India)|Yanam]], in the Godavari delta, and (save for periods of British control) would hold it until 1954.

[[Indian independence movement|India became independent]] from the United Kingdom in 1947. The Nizam wanted to retain the independence of the Princely Hyderabad State from India, but the people of the region launched a movement to join the Indian Union. The state of Hyderabad was forcibly joined to the Republic of India with [[Operation Polo]] in 1948.

In an effort to gain an independent state  based on the lingustic and protect the interests of the Andhra (telugu speaking) people of [[Madras State]], [[Potti Sreeramulu]] fasted until death in 1952. After his death, Andhra attained statehood on 1 November 1953, with [[Kurnool]] as its capital.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/fline/fl2626/stories/20100101262602100.htm |title=Reorganisation, then and now |publisher=Hinduonnet.com |date= |accessdate=7 March 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On 1 November 1956, the [[States Reorganization Act]] merged the Telugu-speaking areas of the former Hyderabad state with the Telugu-speaking areas of the former Madras state to form the state of Vishalandhra, which is named as Andhra Pradesh.&lt;ref name=&quot;Know Hyderabad&quot; /&gt; The city of [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], the former capital of the Hyderabad State, was made the capital of the new state. There were several movements to disintigrate Andhra Pradesh into two States viz. Andhra and Telengana in the late 1960 which are continuing till date.
{{see also|Andhra State|Vishalandhra Movement}}

On 9 December 2009, it was announced that a separation proposal for [[Telangana]] would be introduced to the state assembly.&lt;ref name=&quot;Financial Times&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/7bb4f9e8-e5ae-11de-b5d7-00144feab49a.html |title=/ India / Politics &amp; Society – Protests as India carves up Andhra Pradesh |work=Financial Times  |date=10 December 2009 |accessdate=15 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Controversy arose as to the future status of [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad City]], part of one of the ten districts of Telangana region.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/news/india/home_secretary_to_retract_hyderabad_statement.php |title=Home Secretary retracts Hyderabad statement|publisher=Ndtv.com |date= |accessdate=15 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; This move was opposed by protesters from Andhra and Rayalaseema regions. On 23 December 2009, the government decided to put the decision of bifurcating the state on hold until a consensus is achieved among the different political parties. This agitated supporters of a separate Telangana state.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=&lt;!--Updated 1136 hrs 3 Feb 2010(+5:30 GMT)--&gt;|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/no-consensus-no-telangana-now-centre/107631-37.html?from=tn |title=No consensus, so no Telangana now: Centre – Politics News – IBNLive |publisher=Ibnlive.in.com |date=3 February 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; On 5 January 2010, the Central Government represented by Home Minister P Chidambaram conducted a meeting by inviting all the recognised political parties of AP and recorded their stand on the issue. The Government of India appointed a committee, headed by [[B. N. Srikrishna]], to guide the central government to settle the issue of Telangana amicably.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Srikrishna-panel-to-visit-Hyderabad-from-May-24-6/H1-Article1-547218.aspx |title=Srikrishna panel to visit Hyderabad from May&amp;nbsp;24–26 |work=Hindustan Times |date=22 May 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Srikrishna committee on Telangana|committee]] submitted its report on 30 December 2010, a day before its term was to expire.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/srikrishna-committee-submits-telangana-statehood-report/731163/ |title=Srikrishna Committee submits Telangana statehood report |work=The Indian Express |location=India |date= |accessdate=7 March 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Geography and climate==
[[File:Greater Flamingoes (Phoenicopterus roseus) taking off W2 IMG 9855.jpg|thumb|[[Greater Flamingo]]es (''Phoenicopterus roseus'') taking off Pocharam lake]]
[[Image:Godavari Bridge.JPG|thumb|The railroad bridge between [[Rajahmundry]] and [[Kovvur]]]]
Geographically, Andhra Pradesh is composed of most of the eastern half of the [[Deccan plateau]] and the plains to the east of the [[Eastern Ghats]]. Andhra Pradesh is divided into three regions. The northern part of the plateau is the [[Telangana]] region and the southern part is known as [[Rayalaseema]]. These two regions are separated by the [[River Krishna]]. The third region is [[Coastal Andhra]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.maharashtraweb.com/AndhraPradesh/AndhraPradeshgeography.htm |title=Andhra Pradesh Geography |publisher=Maharashtraweb.com |date=|accessdate=15 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;  The plains to the east of Eastern Ghats form the [[Eastern coastal plains]]. The Eastern Ghats are discontinuous and individual sections have local names. The Kadapa Basin&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.dae.gov.in/amd/regions/scr_cud.htm ]{{Dead link|date=August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; formed by two arching branches of the Eastern Ghats is a mineral rich area. The coastal plains are for the most part delta regions formed by the [[Godavari River|Godavari]], [[River Krishna|Krishna]], and[[Penner River|Penner]] rivers. The Eastern Ghats are a major dividing line in the state's geography. The Ghats become more pronounced towards the south and extreme north of the coast. The Eastern Ghat region is home to dense tropical forests, while the vegetation becomes sparse as the Ghats give way to the Deccan Plateau, where shrub vegetation is more common. Most of the coastal plains are put to intense agricultural use. The west and southwest parts of Andhra Pradesh have semi-arid conditions.

The climate of Andhra Pradesh varies considerably, depending on the geographical region. Monsoons play a major role in determining the climate of the state. Summers last from March to June. In the coastal plain, the summer temperatures are generally higher than the rest of the state, with temperature ranging between 20 °C and 41 °C.&lt;ref name=&quot;tourisminap.com&quot;&gt;{{cite web|author=Aptdc, Andhra Pradesh Tourism Development Corporation|url=http://www.tourisminap.com/know_ap/index.php |title=APTDC – Andhra Pradesh Tourism Development Corporation|publisher=Tourisminap.com|date=27 May 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

July to September is the seasons for tropical rains in Andhra Pradesh. The state receives heavy rainfall from Southwest Monsoon during these months. About one third of the total rainfall in Andhra Pradesh is brought by the [[Monsoon#Northeast Monsoon|Northeast Monsoon]]. October and November see low-pressure systems and tropical cyclones form in the Bay of Bengal which, along with the Northeast Monsoon, bring rains to the southern and coastal regions of the state. November, December, January, and February are the winter months in Andhra Pradesh. Since the state has a long coastal belt the winters are not very cold. The range of winter temperature is generally 12 °C to 30 °C.&lt;ref name=&quot;tourisminap.com&quot;/&gt;

[[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] is the capital and, along with the adjoining twin city [[Secunderabad]], is the largest city in the state.[[Visakhapatnam]], Andhra Pradesh's main seaport, is the second largest city and is home to the [[Indian Navy]]'s Eastern Naval Command.  Due to its location and proximity to major rail and road routes, [[Vijayawada]] is a major trading center. It is the third largest city of the state, [[Warangal]] the historical city of Andhra Pradesh, comprised of [[Warangal]], [[Hanamkonda]] and [[Kazipet]], which is also called Tri City, is the fourth largest city of Andhra Pradesh followed by [[Tirupati (city)|Tirupati]], [[Rajahmundry]], [[Kakinada]] and [[Guntur]]. Other important cities of the state are [[Karimnagar]], [[Nellore]], [[Nizamabad]], [[Kurnool]], [[Kadapa]], and [[Srikakulam]].

==Demographics==
{{IndiaCensusPop
| title= Population Trend
| 1961= 35983000
| 1971= 43503000
| 1981= 53550000
| 1991= 66508000
| 2001= 75727000
| 2011= 84655533
| estimate=
| est year=
| est ref=
| footnote=Source:Census of India&lt;ref name=&quot;Population Characteristics - Andhra Pradesh&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://budget.ap.gov.in/tab1_1.htm|title=Population Characteristics&amp;nbsp;— Andra Pradesh|work=Census of India|publisher=budget.ap.gov.in|accessdate=4 June 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;
|state=
}}

[[Telugu language|Telugu]] is the official language of the state, spoken by 83% of the population. Major linguistic minority groups include [[Urdu language|Urdu]] (8.63%), [[Hindi]] (3.23%),  and [[Tamil language|Tamil]] (1.01%).

Other languages spoken in Andhra Pradesh by less than 1% each are [[Marathi language|Marathi]] (0.8%), [[Kannada language|Kannada]](0.74%), and [[Oriya language|Oriya]] (0.44%). Languages spoken by less than 0.2% of the population include [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] (0.08%), [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] (0.06%), [[Bengali language|Bengali]] (0.05%), [[Nepali language|Gorkhali/Nepali]] (0.03%), [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] (0.01%) and [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]](0.01%).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url= http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/Census_Data_Online/Language/Statement3.htm |title= Distribution of 10,000 Persons by Language&amp;nbsp;— India, States and Union Territories – 2001 |accessdate=16 June 2010 |last= |first= |coauthors= |year= 2001 |work=|publisher=Office of the Registrar General &amp; Census Commissioner, India}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The main ethnic group of Andhra Pradesh is the [[Telugu people]], who are primarily [[Dravidian people|Dravidians]].

Andhra Pradesh ranks tenth compared to all Indian States in the Human Development Index scores&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.aponline.gov.in/Apportal/HumanDevelopmentReport2007/APHDR_2007_Chapter2.pdf|title=Human Development Report 2007|publisher=APonline.gov.in|accessdate=15 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; with a score of 0.416.

The National Council of Applied Economic Research district analysis in 2001 reveals that [[Khammam district|Khammam]], [[Krishna district|Krishna]], [[West Godavari]], [[Chittoor district|Chittoor]], and [[Medak District|Medak]] are the five districts with the highest [[Human Development Index]]scores in ascending order in rural AP. The data show that the poor make up 16.3 per cent of the total population in rural AP and expenditure on consumption is around 13.5 per cent of the total consumption expenditure. The female literacy rate is 0.66 compared to male literacy rate in rural AP. The district-wise variations for poverty ratio are high and low for the ratio of female/male literacy rate.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ncaer.org/Downloads/WorkingPapers/WP99.pdf|title=Human Development Index for Rural Andhra Pradesh|author=Beti, Jatinder S.; Ramachandran, Dr. H.|date=December 2008|publisher=National Council of Applied Economic Research|work=www.ncaer.org|accessdate=15 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Economy==
[[File:Cotton picking in India.jpg|thumb|250 px|left|Woman picking cotton in Andhra Pradesh]]
{{Main|Economy of Andhra Pradesh}}
{| class=&quot;wikitable&quot; style=&quot;float:right;&quot;
|+ GDP by year
! Year
! State GDP ({{Indian Rupee}} MM)
|-
| 1980
|{{INR}}81,910
|-
| 1985
|{{INR}}152,660
|-
| 1990
|{{INR}}333,360
|-
| 1995
|{{INR}}798,540
|-
| 2000
|{{INR}}1,401,190
|-
| 2007
|{{INR}}2,294,610
|}

Andhra Pradesh's GSDP for 2010 was estimated at $100.35 billion in current prices. The state ranks third in terms of overall Gross State Product among all the states of the Indian Union.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Indian_states_by_GDP#cite_note-0}}&lt;/ref&gt; In terms of per capita GSDP the state compares very favorably with other large states. In the 2010 list by ''[[Forbes Magazine]]'', there are Seven from Andhra Pradesh among the top 100 richest Indians.{{citation needed|date=February 2011}}

Agriculture has been the chief source of income for the state's economy. Andhra Pradesh is an exporter of many agricultural products. Four important rivers of India, the [[Godavari River|Godavari]], [[Krishna River|Krishna]], [[Penner River|Penna]], and [[Tungabhadra River|Thungabhadra]] flow through the state, providing irrigation. Rice, [[sugarcane]], [[cotton]], [[Chili pepper]], [[mango]], and tobacco are the local crops. Recently, crops used for [[Vegetable fats and oils|vegetable oil]] production such as [[sunflower]] and [[peanut]]s have gained favour. There are many multi-state irrigation projects in development, including [[Godavari River Basin Irrigation Projects]] and [[Nagarjuna Sagar Dam]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://agri.ap.nic.in|title=Agriculture Dept. of Andhra Pradesh}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name = &quot;dfljos&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.apind.gov.in/indussectors.html|title=Key Sectors of Andhra Pradesh}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The service sector of the state accounts for 43% of the gross state domestic product (GSDP) and employs 20% of the work force.&lt;ref name = &quot;dfljos&quot;/&gt; Andhra Pradesh economy has registered over 5.5% annual economic growth rate during the last two decades.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}} The state is one of the most industrially developed states of India.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}}

Andhra Pradesh ranks second in India in terms of mineral wealth. The state has about one third of India's [[limestone]] reserves, estimated at about 30&amp;nbsp;billion tonnes. The [[Krishna Godavari Basin]] has huge reserves of natural gas and petroleum. The state has a large amount of coal reserves.&lt;ref name = &quot;dfljos&quot;/&gt; The state ranks first nationwide in [[States of India by installed power capacity|hydro electricity generation]], with a national market share of over 11%. Andhra Pradesh has the second largest power generating utility in the country, with an installed capacity of around 10,650 MW. The two cheapest sources of thermal power generation – coal and natural gas – are in abundance.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}}

===Information technology===
{{Main|Software industry in Andhra Pradesh}}
[[File:Hitec city.jpg|thumb|[[HITEC City#Cyber Towers|Cyber Towers]] at [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]]]]
In 2004–2005, Andhra Pradesh was at the second position{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}} in the list of top [[information technology]] exporting states of India. The IT exports from the state were {{INR}}8,270 crores in 2004–2005 ($1.8&amp;nbsp;billion).&lt;ref&gt;http://finance.indiainfo.com/news/2005/05/11/1105it-exports.html {{Dead link|date=December 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;{{Failed verification|date=August 2010}} The IT sector is expanding at a rate of 52.3% every year. The IT exports reached  {{INR}}19,000 crores ($4.5&amp;nbsp;billion) in 2006–2007, contributed to 14 per cent of total IT exports of the nation and ranked fourth in India.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.pppinindia.com/business-opportunities-andhra-pradesh.asp]{{Dead link|date=August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Biotechnology===
The field of biotechnology in Andra pradesh is developing day by day.and the government is not funding money for research in the field of bio tech,some  universities like Andhra university ,Nagarjuna universities , etc. are not able to run the course of bio-tech because of lack of funds  
The state capital of Hyderabad is considered to be the bulk drug capital of India. Four of the top ten pharmaceutical companies are from the state.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}} Major pharma companies from the state are:
* [[Dr. Reddy's Laboratories]]
* Novartis
* [[Hetero Drugs Ltd]]
* Aurobindo Pharma
* Vasudha Pharma
* Divi Laboratories

